UNDOING GIT

Here is a clear, step-by-step guide on **undoing changes in Git**, based on your workflow and using your GitHub account (MMohamed-1-sudo). This covers the most common real-world scenarios.

---

## Step 1: Start from a Clean State

Always begin by switching to your main branch and pulling the latest changes:

```bash
git checkout main
git pull
```

This ensures you are working with the latest version of your project.

---

## Step 2: Create and Commit a File (Setup Example)

Create a file and commit it:

```bash
echo "Original line" > undo.txt
git add undo.txt
git commit -m "Test commit"
git push
```

Now you have a committed file to work with.

---

## Case 1: Undo Changes That Are NOT Staged

You edited a file but have not added it yet.

Make a bad change:

```bash
echo "Bad change" >> undo.txt
cat undo.txt
```

You realise this change is wrong and want to discard it.

Restore the file to the last committed version:

```bash
git restore undo.txt
```

Check again:

```bash
cat undo.txt
```

The file is now back to its original state.

---

## Case 2: Undo Changes That Are Already Staged

Make another change:

```bash
echo "Another bad line" >> undo.txt
git add undo.txt
```

Now the file is staged, but you want to undo that staging.

Unstage the file:

```bash
git restore --staged undo.txt
```

Check status:

```bash
git status
```

The file is now back to unstaged (red), but your changes still exist.

If needed, you can now fully discard them using:

```bash
git restore undo.txt
```

---

## Case 3: Undo a Commit That Has NOT Been Pushed

Make a bad commit:

```bash
echo "Oops commit" >> undo.txt
git add undo.txt
git commit -m "Bad commit"
```

Now you want to undo this commit.

### Option 1: Keep changes staged

```bash
git reset --soft HEAD~1
```

* Removes the commit
* Keeps changes staged

---

### Option 2: Keep changes but unstage them

```bash
git reset --mixed HEAD~1
```

* Removes the commit
* Keeps changes in the file
* Unstages them

---

### Option 3: Delete commit and changes completely

```bash
git reset --hard HEAD~1
```

* Removes the commit
* Deletes all associated changes

This is destructive, so use it carefully.

---

## Case 4: Undo a Commit That Has BEEN Pushed

Make a mistake and push it:

```bash
echo "Production mistake" >> undo.txt
git add undo.txt
git commit -m "Accidental commit"
git push
```

Now the mistake is already on GitHub.

Do NOT use reset here. Instead, safely revert it:

```bash
git revert HEAD
```

* This creates a new commit that undoes the previous one
* It is safe for shared repositories

Then push:

```bash
git push
```

Now your mistake is reversed without rewriting history.

---

## Step 5: View History and Recover Work

To see commit history:

```bash
git log --oneline
```

This shows a simple list of commits.

---

To see all actions (including resets and deleted commits):

```bash
git reflog
```

This is very powerful because it tracks everything you have done, even if you reset or deleted commits. You can recover lost work from here.

---

## Final Understanding

You now have four key ways to undo changes:

* `git restore` → discard file changes
* `git restore --staged` → unstage files
* `git reset` → undo commits (local only, careful use)
* `git revert` → safely undo pushed commits

Safe methods:

* restore
* revert

More dangerous methods:

* reset --hard

---

Understanding when to use each of these is essential when working with Git, especially in team environments on GitHub.

### Why Git Stash is Useful

When working on a project, you will often be in the middle of a task when something urgent comes up, such as fixing a bug or switching branches. Instead of committing incomplete work or losing your changes, **Git stash allows you to temporarily save your work and come back to it later**. It acts like a safe holding area, letting you switch context quickly without affecting your commit history or breaking your workflow on GitHub.

---

## Step 1: Start from a Clean and Updated State

Make sure your repository is up to date:

```bash
git pull
```

Check that there are no pending changes:

```bash
git status
```

---

## Step 2: Create Some Work in Progress

Simulate working on a feature:

```bash
echo "Incomplete work" > feature.txt
git add feature.txt
```

Add more changes that are not staged:

```bash
echo "More changes not staged" >> feature.txt
```

At this point:

* Some changes are staged
* Some are not staged
* Work is incomplete

---

## Step 3: Stash Your Work

You are now asked to switch tasks. Save your work using stash:

```bash
git stash push -m "Work in progress on feature.txt"
```

Now check your status:

```bash
git status
```

Your working directory is clean. Your changes are safely stored in the stash.

---

## Step 4: Switch Context and Do Other Work

Now you can work on something else, such as a hotfix:

```bash
echo "Hotfix applied" > hotfix.txt
git add hotfix.txt
git commit -m "Apply hotfix on main"
git push
```

You have successfully switched tasks without losing your previous work.

---

## Step 5: View Your Stashed Work

To see your saved work:

```bash
git stash list
```

You will see your stash entry with the message you provided.

---

## Step 6: Restore Your Stashed Work

Bring your work back:

```bash
git stash apply
```

* This restores your changes
* The stash is still saved

Check your files:

```bash
git status
```

Your previous work is now back in your working directory.

---

## Step 7: Apply and Remove the Stash (Optional)

If you want to restore and delete the stash in one step:

```bash
git stash pop
```

* Applies the stash
* Removes it from the stash list

---

## Step 8: Continue Your Work

Now commit and push your restored work:

```bash
git add feature.txt
git commit -m "Continue feature work"
git push
```

---

## Step 9: Clean Up All Stashes (Optional)

If you no longer need any stashes:

```bash
git stash clear
```

This removes all stored stashes permanently.

---

## Final Understanding

Git stash helps you:

* Save incomplete work without committing
* Quickly switch between tasks or branches
* Resume work exactly where you left off

Typical workflow:

* Work on a feature
* Stash changes
* Switch to another task
* Apply or pop the stash
* Continue working

---

This is a very common workflow used by developers working on shared projects in GitHub, especially when handling interruptions or urgent fixes.


### Why Cleaning Commit History is Important

When working on a project, especially in a team, your commit history should be clear and meaningful. Instead of having many small or messy commits like “fix”, “update”, or “test”, you can **combine them into a single clean commit** using rebase. This makes your project history easier to read, review, and maintain on GitHub.

